Note:
PERSISTENT SET - HAMT-based Immutable Set Tier 0 Primitive

This file implements an immutable Set as a thin wrapper over the
PersistentMap HAMT. Each set element is stored as a (key = element,
value = 1) entry. Insertion and removal yield new sets sharing
structure with the old set.

The wrapper layer is needed (rather than reusing PersistentMap as the
concrete type) so the set-oriented API names are first-class and the
value-as-1 invariant is internal to the implementation.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/persistent_map.runa" as PMap

Let PSET_HEADER_SIZE be 8

@Reasoning
Create an empty persistent set.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate header; backing PMap created via pmap_create.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pset_create" returns Integer:
    Let ps be proc allocate from Layout with PSET_HEADER_SIZE
    If ps is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pm be proc pmap_create from PMap
    If pm is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with ps
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ps, 0, pm
    Return ps
End Process

@Reasoning
Destroy the persistent set.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Destroy underlying PMap, free header.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-owned.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pset_destroy" takes ps as Integer returns Integer:
    If ps is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pm be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ps, 0
    If pm is not equal to 0:
        proc pmap_destroy from PMap with pm
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with ps
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Persistent add. Returns a new set; the old set is still valid.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Call pmap_assoc on underlying map with value = 1.
2) Allocate new set header; install new map.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pset_add" takes ps as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    If ps is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let old_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ps, 0
    Let new_map be proc pmap_assoc from PMap with old_map, value, 1
    If new_map is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let new_ps be proc allocate from Layout with PSET_HEADER_SIZE
    If new_ps is equal to 0:
        proc pmap_destroy from PMap with new_map
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_ps, 0, new_map
    Return new_ps
End Process

@Reasoning
Contains predicate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegate to pmap_contains.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pset_contains" takes ps as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    If ps is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pm be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ps, 0
    Return proc pmap_contains from PMap with pm, value
End Process

@Reasoning
Size accessor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegate to pmap_size.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pset_size" takes ps as Integer returns Integer:
    If ps is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pm be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ps, 0
    Return proc pmap_size from PMap with pm
End Process

@Reasoning
Empty predicate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Delegate to pmap_is_empty.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pset_is_empty" takes ps as Integer returns Integer:
    If ps is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let pm be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ps, 0
    Return proc pmap_is_empty from PMap with pm
End Process

@Reasoning
Persistent remove. Returns a new set whose backing map has the
underlying key dissociated. The old set remains valid.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Call pmap_dissoc on the underlying map.
2) Allocate a new set header pointing at the new map.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pset_remove" takes ps as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    If ps is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let old_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ps, 0
    Let new_map be proc pmap_dissoc from PMap with old_map, value
    If new_map is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let new_ps be proc allocate from Layout with PSET_HEADER_SIZE
    If new_ps is equal to 0:
        proc pmap_destroy from PMap with new_map
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_ps, 0, new_map
    Return new_ps
End Process

@Reasoning
Union of two persistent sets: returns a new set containing every
element that appears in either input. Original sets are unchanged.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Start with a path-copy of set_a's backing map.
2) Collect every key from set_b's underlying map into a buffer.
3) For each key not already in the running result, fold it in via
   pmap_assoc. Each iteration allocates a new map; the intermediate
   maps are destroyed so memory accumulation is bounded to the final
   union map plus one transient.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(|B| log(|A|+|B|)). The cost is dominated by the smaller-set
keys being folded into the larger map.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pset_union" takes set_a as Integer, set_b as Integer returns Integer:
    If set_a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If set_b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let map_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with set_a, 0
    Let map_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with set_b, 0
    Note: Build a fresh result map. Fold every key from set_a, then
    Note: every key from set_b. HAMT assoc is idempotent: a duplicate
    Note: key produces a map with the same logical contents. Keeping
    Note: result independent of map_a / map_b lets the caller destroy
    Note: each independently.
    Let running be proc pmap_create from PMap
    If running is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let keys_a be proc pmap_collect_keys from PMap with map_a
    If keys_a is equal to 0:
        proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with keys_a, 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let k_off be 8 plus (i multiplied by 8)
        Let k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with keys_a, k_off
        Let next_map be proc pmap_assoc from PMap with running, k, 1
        If next_map is equal to 0:
            proc deallocate from Layout with keys_a
            proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
            Return 0
        End If
        proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
        Set running to next_map
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc deallocate from Layout with keys_a
    Let keys_b be proc pmap_collect_keys from PMap with map_b
    If keys_b is equal to 0:
        proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with keys_b, 0
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than count_b:
        Let k_off2 be 8 plus (j multiplied by 8)
        Let k2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with keys_b, k_off2
        Let next_map2 be proc pmap_assoc from PMap with running, k2, 1
        If next_map2 is equal to 0:
            proc deallocate from Layout with keys_b
            proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
            Return 0
        End If
        proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
        Set running to next_map2
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While
    proc deallocate from Layout with keys_b
    Let new_ps be proc allocate from Layout with PSET_HEADER_SIZE
    If new_ps is equal to 0:
        proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_ps, 0, running
    Return new_ps
End Process

@Reasoning
Intersection of two persistent sets: returns a new set containing
every element that appears in both inputs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Iterate the keys of the smaller of the two sets; for each key, if it
exists in the other set, add it to a fresh result set. Starting from
the empty set keeps the running structure small.

To keep the comparison directional and simple, the implementation
iterates set_a's keys and tests pmap_contains against set_b. (A more
optimal version would pick the smaller of the two; for correctness
and clarity the direction is fixed.)
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(|A| log |B|).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pset_intersect" takes set_a as Integer, set_b as Integer returns Integer:
    If set_a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If set_b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let map_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with set_a, 0
    Let map_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with set_b, 0
    Let keys_buf be proc pmap_collect_keys from PMap with map_a
    If keys_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let key_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with keys_buf, 0
    Let running be proc pmap_create from PMap
    If running is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with keys_buf
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than key_count:
        Let k_off be 8 plus (i multiplied by 8)
        Let k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with keys_buf, k_off
        Let in_b be proc pmap_contains from PMap with map_b, k
        If in_b is equal to 1:
            Let next_map be proc pmap_assoc from PMap with running, k, 1
            If next_map is equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Layout with keys_buf
                proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
                Return 0
            End If
            proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
            Set running to next_map
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc deallocate from Layout with keys_buf
    Let new_ps be proc allocate from Layout with PSET_HEADER_SIZE
    If new_ps is equal to 0:
        proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_ps, 0, running
    Return new_ps
End Process

@Reasoning
Set difference: returns a new set containing every element of set_a
that is not in set_b. set_a \\ set_b.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Iterate set_a's keys; for each key not in set_b, add it to a fresh
result set. Symmetric to pset_intersect but the membership test is
inverted.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(|A| log |B|).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "pset_diff" takes set_a as Integer, set_b as Integer returns Integer:
    If set_a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If set_b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let map_a be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with set_a, 0
    Let map_b be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with set_b, 0
    Let keys_buf be proc pmap_collect_keys from PMap with map_a
    If keys_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let key_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with keys_buf, 0
    Let running be proc pmap_create from PMap
    If running is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with keys_buf
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than key_count:
        Let k_off be 8 plus (i multiplied by 8)
        Let k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with keys_buf, k_off
        Let in_b be proc pmap_contains from PMap with map_b, k
        If in_b is equal to 0:
            Let next_map be proc pmap_assoc from PMap with running, k, 1
            If next_map is equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Layout with keys_buf
                proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
                Return 0
            End If
            proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
            Set running to next_map
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc deallocate from Layout with keys_buf
    Let new_ps be proc allocate from Layout with PSET_HEADER_SIZE
    If new_ps is equal to 0:
        proc pmap_destroy from PMap with running
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_ps, 0, running
    Return new_ps
End Process
